<subSubSection id="D15BE5F8FE05F1BEAB83815B2CE59BEB" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C7D9C9E213D1964DB6C7ADEE3310B43E" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FCD7344DE7014F82AEE4DEEBAF398470" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Madagascar: Antsiranana, Toamasina.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0B869F84BA570B8444757CCF0791A789" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="967A5600CF596ECBC54A62110A269A91" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9845C0A8676EEE86B7C0B12C2BE5904E" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The specific name is from the Latin 
<emphasis id="56A25B2194DC61F51BEAE5FD23E2A736" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">brevis</emphasis>
, referring to the short parameres of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="594467F7B96E292181B6BFEE8BC4DCB2" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="23881FCBB8D6AA92256917979A8BAFEA" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="56849FD6D518B5014E148FE8C329A5BE" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The short parameres of the male genitalia place this species close to 
<taxonomicName id="4B12BCF5098B4AC30EABE037BD62BE18" authorityName="Bischoff" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seyrigi">
<emphasis id="4F404D5FE394451A3BF057FEFC98C691" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys seyrigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, the parameres of 
<taxonomicName id="705BD129A8093371EA245844802B1666" authorityName="Smith &amp; Tripotin" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="9A616D9C77184C972E247A1C40D07C56" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shorter and broader than long whereas those of 
<taxonomicName id="0FADD39F8874C183AF33CE502BC44C6E" authorityName="Bischoff" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seyrigi">
<emphasis id="6C4C2C858A1C1B4137FD484766C52CCE" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys seyrigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are about as broad as long (
<figureCitation id="F21C2623E45A0D14288AFF0068CE9650" captionStart="Figures 4–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 4 - 7. Orthogonalys brevis, male paratype. 4 Head, front view. 5 Head, dorsal view. 6 Apex of abdomen and genitalia, lateral view. 7 Genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11358" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AAD07B67F3993642AD25919B791879E6" captionStart="Figures 37–39" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 37 - 39. Orthogonalys seyrigi, male. 37 Head, front view. 38 Head, dorsal view. 39 Apex of abdomen and genitalia, lateral view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11368" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">39</figureCitation>
) The color of 
<taxonomicName id="CCD1094BEC3618AC12D7C5173EDB97F8" authorityName="Smith &amp; Tripotin" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="1537DD0ED50E494CB59029BEE88A747F" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is entirely different than in 
<taxonomicName id="D3E87DFF0FCD42C7350D17BAC6B40C78" authorityName="Bischoff" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seyrigi">
<emphasis id="7A85B6D8FCCB37E93E158ED13EE91204" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys seyrigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and more similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4581F9A488342A645D30675AFB6535D4" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="FB4B1B45638188137CC61757D8B00686" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the almost entirely orange mesosoma and metasoma. The color of the head is consistently different than in other 
<taxonomicName id="7D6F419EC6EC2A62016F1B1FB9030AB1" authorityName="Schulz" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48A7135573DDEC83EB4DE045088995CE" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with more white across the frons, which is not interrupted with black, except sometime for a very narrow medial line, and the entirely black gena (
<figureCitation id="AAB20527B4D8F2D2D77CE187B7966520" captionStart="Figures 4–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 4 - 7. Orthogonalys brevis, male paratype. 4 Head, front view. 5 Head, dorsal view. 6 Apex of abdomen and genitalia, lateral view. 7 Genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11358" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 4, 5</figureCitation>
). The metasoma of 
<taxonomicName id="0C4869AE5A999AC86B6AD8309D867BCC" authorityName="Smith &amp; Tripotin" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="C941A9C1033CD15687444290C81E2243" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Orthogonalys brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost entirely orange with only apical segment white and the penultimate segment mostly black.
</paragraph>
